    "### Observations:\n",
    "\n",
    "- After transformation, the RFM variables exhibit approximately symmetric distributions, as evidenced by near-zero skewness values, indicating that the data is suitably conditioned for standard normalization techniques.\n",
    "  \n",
    "-  Although the boxplots reveal a small number of remaining outliers, these are not sufficiently extreme or influential to distort the scaling process or materially affect distance-based computations in K-Means clustering.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Given the well-behaved nature of the transformed distributions, the use of RobustScaler is not justified, as its primary purpose is to mitigate the impact of severe outliers or highly skewed data—conditions that are no longer present following transformation.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Therefore, StandardScaler is adopted as the primary normalization method for feature standardization, as it ensures equal contribution of all variables while preserving the variance structure required for meaningful cluster formation."
   ]
  },
