   "source": [
    "## 3.1. K-Means Overview\n",
    "\n",
    "K-Means is a popular unsupervised machine learning algorithm used to partition data into K distinct clusters based on feature similarity. The algorithm seeks to minimize the within-cluster sum of squares (WCSS) by grouping observations so that those within the same cluster are as similar as possible while those in different clusters are as dissimilar as possible.\n",
    "\n",
    "The algorithm operates iteratively through the following steps:\n",
    "- Initialize: Randomly select K initial cluster centroids (or use the K-Means++ initialization method to improve centroid selection).\n",
    "- Assign: Assign each observation to the nearest centroid based on Euclidean distance.\n",
    "- Update: Recalculate each centroid as the mean of all observations assigned to its cluster.\n",
    "- Repeat: Continue the assignment and update steps until the centroids no longer change significantly or the maximum number of iterations is reached.\n",
    "\n",
    "The result is a set of clusters that minimizes the variation within each cluster while maximizing the separation between clusters.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this project, K-Means is applied to the transformed and scaled RFM features to identify customer groups with similar purchasing behaviors.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Advantages**\n",
    "- Simple to understand and implement.\n",
    "- Computationally efficient and scalable to large datasets.\n",
    "- Produces easily interpretable customer segments.\n",
    "- Performs well when clusters are compact and well separated.\n",
    "- Works effectively with RFM analysis for customer segmentation.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Limitations**\n",
    "- Requires the number of clusters (K) to be specified in advance.\n",
    "- Sensitive to the initial placement of centroids, although K-Means++ reduces this issue.\n",
    "- Sensitive to outliers, which can influence cluster centroids.\n",
    "- Assumes clusters are approximately spherical and of similar size.\n",
    "- Requires properly scaled numerical features for optimal performance."
   ]
