   "source": [
    "## 3.2. Determine Optimal Number of Clusters (K)\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3.2.1. Overview\n",
    "\n",
    "The performance of K-Means clustering depends heavily on the choice of the number of clusters (K). Selecting too few clusters may lead to overly broad and heterogeneous groups, whereas selecting too many clusters may produce fragmented segments that are difficult to interpret.\n",
    "\n",
    "To identify the optimal number of clusters, three internal cluster validation techniques are employed:\n",
    "- Elbow Method\n",
    "- Silhouette Method\n",
    "- Calinski–Harabasz Index\n",
    "\n",
    "These methods evaluate clustering quality from different perspectives and are used jointly to obtain a robust estimate of the optimal number of clusters.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Method                  | Primary Objective                                                         | Optimal K Criterion       |\n",
    "| ----------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------- |\n",
    "| Elbow Method            | Minimize within-cluster variation                                         | Elbow point in WCSS curve |\n",
    "| Silhouette Method       | Maximize cohesion and separation                                          | Highest silhouette score  |\n",
    "| Calinski–Harabasz Index | Maximize between-cluster dispersion relative to within-cluster dispersion | Highest CH score          |\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3.2.2. Elbow Method\n",
    "\n",
    "#### a) Definition\n",
    "\n",
    "The Elbow Method determines the optimal number of clusters by evaluating the Within-Cluster Sum of Squares (WCSS), also known as inertia, across different values of K. K-Means aims to minimize WCSS, which measures the total squared distance between each data point and its assigned cluster centroid.\n",
    "\n",
    "Formally, the K-Means objective function is defined as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$WCSS = \\min_{\\{C_1,\\dots,C_K\\}} \\sum_{k=1}^{K} \\sum_{x_i \\in C_k} \\|x_i - \\mu_k\\|^2$\n",
    "where:\n",
    "- $C_k$ represents cluster $k$  \n",
    "- $x_i$ denotes a data point  \n",
    "- $\\mu_k$ is the centroid of cluster $k$\n",
    "- $\\|x_i - \\mu_k\\|^2$ is the squared Euclidean distance between the point and the centroid\n",
    "- The centroids  $\\mu_k$  are computed as the arithmetic mean of all points assigned to cluster $C_k$ , which minimizes the sum of squared distances within each cluster.\n",
    "\n",
    "As K increases, WCSS decreases because clusters become smaller and more compact: the  observations become more closely grouped around their respective centroids. However, after a certain point, the improvement becomes marginal. The optimal K is identified by plotting K against WCSS and selecting the point where the rate of decrease slows significantly, forming an “elbow” shape in the curve. This point represents a balance between model complexity and cluster compactness.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "#### b) Procedure\n",
    "\n",
    "**1) Select a range of K values** : Define a range of candidate cluster numbers (e.g., K = 1 to 10 or 2 to 10). The selection of this range is typically guided by dataset size, domain knowledge and interpretability constraints.\n",
    "\n",
    "**2) Fit the K-Means algorithm for each value of K**: For each candidate value of K, fit a K-Means model until convergence using the standard K-Means iterative procedure described in the previous section.\n",
    "\n",
    "**3) Compute Within-Cluster Sum of Squares (WCSS)** : After the model converges, compute the Within-Cluster Sum of Squares (WCSS), which measures the total squared Euclidean distance between each observation and the centroid of its assigned cluster.\n",
    "\n",
    "**4) Store WCSS values**: Record the WCSS value corresponding to each tested value of K for further analysis.\n",
    "\n",
    "**5) Construct the Elbow Curve**: Plot the number of clusters (K) on the x-axis against the corresponding WCSS values on the y-axis to obtain the elbow curve.\n",
    "\n",
    "**6) Identify the Optimal Number of Clusters**: The optimal K is determined by identifying the point at which the rate of decrease in WCSS begins to slow significantly, forming a characteristic “elbow” shape in the curve. This point represents a trade-off between:\n",
    "   - model complexity (number of clusters)\n",
    "   - cluster compactness (minimization of WCSS)\n",
    "Beyond this point, increasing K yields only marginal improvements in clustering performance.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "### 3.2.3. Silhouette Method\n",
    "\n",
    "#### a) Definition\n",
    "\n",
    "The Silhouette Method is a cluster validation technique used to determine the optimal number of clusters by evaluating how well each observation fits within its assigned cluster compared to other clusters. Unlike the Elbow Method, which primarily focuses on cluster compactness, the Silhouette Method simultaneously evaluates:\n",
    "- `intra-cluster cohesion` (how closely observations are grouped within the same cluster), and\n",
    "- `inter-cluster separation` (how distinct clusters are from one another).\n",
    "\n",
    "For each observation $i$, the silhouette coefficient is defined as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$s(i) = \\frac{b(i) - a(i)}{\\max(a(i), b(i))}$\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $a(i)$ represents the average distance between observation $i$ and all other observations belonging to the same cluster\n",
    "- $b(i)$ denotes the minimum average distance between observation $i$ and observations in the nearest neighboring cluster\n",
    "- $s(i)$ is the silhouette coefficient associated with observation $i$\n",
    "\n",
    "The silhouette coefficient ranges from $-1$ to $+1$:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $s(i) \\approx +1$: the observation is well matched to its own cluster and poorly matched to neighboring clusters\n",
    "- $s(i) \\approx 0$: the observation lies near the boundary between two clusters\n",
    "- $s(i) < 0$: the observation may be incorrectly assigned to a cluster\n",
    "\n",
    "The overall silhouette score for a clustering solution is obtained by calculating the average silhouette coefficient across all observations:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\\text{Silhouette Score} = \\frac{1}{n}\\sum_{i=1}^{n}s(i)$   where \\(n\\) is the total number of observations.\n",
    "\n",
    "The optimal number of clusters is identified as the value of $K$ that maximizes the average silhouette score, indicating a clustering structure characterized by high intra-cluster cohesion and strong inter-cluster separation.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### b) Procedure\n",
    "\n",
    "**1) Select a Range of K Values**\n",
    "\n",
    "**2) Fit the K-Means algorithm for each value of K**\n",
    "\n",
    "**3) Compute the Intra-Cluster Distance $a(i)$**: For each observation, compute the average distance between the observation and all other observations belonging to the same cluster.\n",
    "\n",
    "**4) Compute the Nearest-Cluster Distance $b(i)$** : For each observation, compute the average distance between the observation and all observations belonging to neighboring clusters, then retain the minimum of these average distances.\n",
    "\n",
    "**5) Compute the Silhouette Coefficient**: Using $a(i)$ and $b(i)$, calculate the silhouette coefficient for each observation:\n",
    "\n",
    "$s(i) = \\frac{b(i) - a(i)}{\\max(a(i), b(i))}$\n",
    "\n",
    "**6) Compute the Average Silhouette Score**: Calculate the mean silhouette coefficient across all observations for each tested value of $K$.\n",
    "\n",
    " **7) Construct the Silhouette Curve**: Plot the number of clusters ($K$) on the x-axis against the corresponding average silhouette scores on the y-axis.\n",
    "\n",
    " **8) Identify the Optimal Number of Clusters**: The optimal number of clusters is determined by selecting the value of $K$ associated with the highest average silhouette score.\n",
    "\n",
    "A higher silhouette score indicates:\n",
    "- greater cohesion within clusters,\n",
    "- better separation between clusters, and\n",
    "- improved overall clustering quality.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "### 3.2.4. Calinski–Harabasz Index\n",
    "\n",
    "#### a) Definition \n",
    "\n",
    "The Calinski–Harabasz Index (also known as the Variance Ratio Criterion) is an internal clustering validation metric used to assess the quality of a clustering solution based on the ratio of between-cluster dispersion to within-cluster dispersion. Unlike the Elbow Method, which primarily focuses on within-cluster compactness, the Calinski–Harabasz Index evaluates both:\n",
    "- inter-cluster separation (how distinct clusters are from one another), and\n",
    "- intra-cluster cohesion (how compact the observations are within each cluster).\n",
    "\n",
    "The index is defined as :\n",
    "$CH = \\dfrac{\\mathrm{tr}(B_K)}{K - 1} \\Big/ \\dfrac{\\mathrm{tr}(W_K)}{n - K}$\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "- $n$: total number of observations  \n",
    "- $K$: number of clusters  \n",
    "- $B_K$: between-cluster dispersion matrix  \n",
    "- $W_K$: within-cluster dispersion matrix  \n",
    "- $\\mathrm{tr}(\\cdot)$: trace operator (sum of diagonal elements of a matrix)\n",
    "\n",
    "The Calinski–Harabasz Index measures the ratio of between-cluster dispersion to within-cluster dispersion, adjusted for the number of clusters and observations.\n",
    "\n",
    "A higher Calinski–Harabasz score indicates greater separation between clusters, and more compact and well-defined cluster structures.\n",
    "\n",
    "The optimal number of clusters is identified as the value of K that maximizes the Calinski–Harabasz Index, indicating the most distinct and well-structured clustering solution.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "#### b) Procedure\n",
    "\n",
    "A procedure similar to the Silhouette Method is followed:\n",
    "- **Define a range of candidate values for K**.\n",
    "- **Fit K-Means clustering for each value of K**.\n",
    "- **Compute the Calinski–Harabasz Index**.\n",
    "- **Record the score for each value of K**.\n",
    "- **Plot K against the corresponding CH scores**.\n",
    "- **Select the value of K that maximizes the index**.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**Note**: \n",
    "\n",
    "The Elbow Method is a visual heuristic technique, and the identification of the elbow point may involve some degree of subjective interpretation depending on the dataset structure. Therefore, it is often recommended to complement it with additional validation methods, such as Silhouette\n",
    "Analysis.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Silhouette Method provides a more quantitative evaluation of clustering quality than the Elbow Method because it explicitly measures both cluster cohesion and cluster separation. However, its computation can become computationally expensive for large datasets since pairwise distances between observations must be calculated.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Calinski–Harabasz Index is computationally efficient and widely used for cluster validation, particularly in K-Means clustering. However, like other internal metrics, it tends to favor well-separated, convex cluster structures and may be less effective when clusters have irregular shapes or varying densities."
   ]
  },
