    "### Interpretations\n",
    "\n",
    "**Elbow Method (WCSS)**\n",
    "\n",
    "- The automated elbow detection method (KneeLocator) suggests K = 4 as the optimal number of clusters, as shown in the figure. However, the elbow method alone can be subjective, particularly when the WCSS curve decreases gradually without a clearly defined \"elbow.\n",
    "\n",
    "- To validate this choice, the percentage reduction in WCSS between consecutive values of K was analyzed. The reduction decreases from approximately 18.7% (K = 2 → 3) to 16.1% (K = 3 → 4) and continues to decline gradually afterward (12.2%, 11.0%, 10.2%, 8.1%, and 7.3% ), indicating diminishing returns from adding more clusters.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Therefore, K = 4 represents the point where additional clusters provide limited improvement, as further increases mainly split existing groups rather than capturing meaningful new customer behavior patterns. Based on both the KneeLocator result and the WCSS reduction analysis, K = 4 was selected as the optimal number of clusters for the elbow method.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Silhouette Score**\n",
    "\n",
    "- The Silhouette Score reaches its maximum value at **K = 2** (**0.3319**) and gradually decreases as **K** increases.\n",
    "- This indicates that the two-cluster solution provides the strongest balance between cluster cohesion and separation.\n",
    "- According to this metric, additional clusters result in less clearly separated customer groups.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Calinski–Harabasz Index**\n",
    "\n",
    "- The Calinski–Harabasz Index also reaches its highest value at **K = 2** (**492.79**) before steadily decreasing for larger values of **K**.\n",
    "- This indicates that **K = 2** provides the strongest ratio of between-cluster dispersion to within-cluster dispersion, supporting a compact and well-separated clustering structure.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### Overall Assessment\n",
    "\n",
    "The evaluation metrics highlight a trade-off between statistical clustering quality and segmentation granularity.\n",
    "\n",
    "Increasing the number of clusters from **K = 2** to **K = 4** reduces the WCSS by approximately **31.8%** (from **1465.81** to **999.52**), indicating that the K = 4 solution produces more compact clusters.\n",
