   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6b43d3fd-4d0e-4f39-b484-18b50d66a8f4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    " ### Insights\n",
    "\n",
    "The cluster profiles provide a business-oriented comparison of the two candidate K-Means solutions. While the **K = 2** solution provides a simpler segmentation with broader customer groups, the **K = 4** solution introduces additional behavioral differentiation that may support more targeted customer strategies.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    " **K = 2 Solution**\n",
    "\n",
    "The K = 2 solution separates customers into two broad behavioral groups.\n",
    "\n",
    "* **Cluster 0 (342|43.1% of customers)** includes customers with less recent purchases (**Average Recency = 244.92 days**), lower purchase frequency (**4.27 orders**), and lower spending (**Average Monetary = $1,317.56**). This cluster represents customers with lower engagement and lower customer value.\n",
    "\n",
    "* **Cluster 1 (451|56.9% of customers)** consists of customers with relatively recent purchases (**Average Recency = 74.35 days**), higher purchase frequency (**7.87 orders**), and substantially higher spending (**Average Monetary = $4,094.45**). This cluster represents the higher-value and more engaged customer group identified by the model.\n",
    "\n",
    "Overall, the K = 2 solution effectively separates customers according to their general level of engagement and value. However, the two clusters remain relatively broad and may combine customers with different purchasing behaviors and business needs.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    " **K = 4 Solution**\n",
    "\n",
    "The K = 4 solution provides a more detailed view of customer purchasing patterns by separating customers into four distinct behavioral groups.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Cluster 0 (27.5% of customers)** consists of customers with relatively high purchasing value but lower recent engagement. These customers have an average recency of **196.78 days**, an average purchase frequency of **6.67 orders**, and average spending of **$3,594.53**. Although they have demonstrated strong purchasing activity and value, the longer time since their last purchase suggests that they may require retention-focused strategies to maintain future engagement.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Cluster 1 (20.3% of customers)** represents the least engaged customer segment, with the longest time since purchase (**Average Recency = 359.15 days**), the lowest purchase frequency (**3.53 orders**), and the lowest average spending (**$896.54**). These customers show signs of inactivity and may require reactivation campaigns to encourage future purchases.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Cluster 2 (26.5% of customers)** contains the highest-value customers, with recent purchasing activity (**Average Recency = 42.36 days**), the highest purchase frequency (**9.05 orders**), and the highest average spending (**$4,984.13**). This segment represents the most valuable and loyal customer group and should be prioritized for loyalty programs, VIP campaigns, and exclusive offers.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Cluster 3 (25.7% of customers)** consists of recently active customers, with the lowest average recency (**37.65 days**) but moderate purchase frequency (**5.32 orders**) and spending (**$1,581.29**). These customers demonstrate strong engagement potential but have not yet reached the purchasing level of the highest-value segment, making them suitable targets for upselling and cross-selling initiatives.\n",
    "\n",
    "Compared with the **K = 2** solution, the **K = 4** solution reveals additional differences among customers that are hidden within the broader two-cluster structure. In particular, it separates high-value active customers from recent moderate-value customers, distinguishes valuable customers with declining activity from inactive low-value customers, and provides more actionable segments for targeted marketing, retention, and customer value optimization strategies.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Final decision\n",
    "\n",
    "Although K = 2 represents the stronger clustering solution from a purely statistical perspective, K = 4 provides greater practical value for customer segmentation and business strategy development. The additional clusters reveal meaningful differences in customer purchasing behavior that are not captured by the broader K = 2 solution.\n",
    "\n",
    "Given the objective of this project, which is to identify actionable customer segments, `K = 4 is selected as the final segmentation solution because it provides a more detailed understanding of customer behavior and supports more targeted business actions`."
   ]
  },
